        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>[Shrewsbury]</placeName>
                    <date>1 Sept 1831</date>
                    <salute>Dear Wedgwood,</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>Charles is very grateful for your taking so much trouble &amp; interest in his plans. I made up my mind to give up all objections, if you should not see it in the same view as I did.—</p>
<p>Charles has stated my objections quite fairly &amp; fully—if he still continues in the same mind after further enquiry, I will give him all the assistance in my power.</p>
<p>Many thanks for your kindness— yours | affectionly | R W Darwin<ref target="#foot.f1"/></p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1234.xml">Robert Waring Darwin</ref> must have written this note soon after receiving the foregoing letters and posted it before CD and his uncle arrived later in the day. This and <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1234.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Robert Waring’s</ref> earlier letter to <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_5026.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Josiah Wedgwood II</ref> (<ref target="./DCP-LETT-108.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from R. W. Darwin to Josiah Wedgwood II, 30–1 August 1831</ref>) clearly call for some revision of the conception of CD’s father as stern and unloving.</note>
        </div>        
            
